        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/ls-jan-7-3.jpg" alt="What are inverse ETFs?" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Inverse exchange-traded funds (ETFs) are financial instruments designed to deliver returns opposite to the performance of a specific index or asset. If the underlying index drops by 1%, the inverse ETF aims to increase by approximately 1%, making it popular for hedging or speculating during market downturns.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4"> When ARKK declines, SARK aims to generate positive returns by using derivatives like swaps to achieve the inverse performance of ARKK on a daily basis. If ARKK falls by 1%, SARK is designed to rise by approximately 1%, making it a popular choice for investors looking to hedge or profit from a downturn in ARKK‚Äôs holdings, which include high-growth tech companies.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4"> However, like other inverse ETFs, SARK is meant for short-term use, as compounding effects can distort performance over time. It‚Äôs a powerful tool for traders but requires careful management due to the inherent risks of inverse strategies. contradict EMH.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
